        <div class="tip">
            <p class="Tip-Text" MadCap:autonum="&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #242729;&quot; class=&quot;mcFormatColor&quot;&gt;Tip &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;">Styled variables do not allow for partial- or character-level styling within a variable.  If you need to style more than the variable as a whole, it is recommended to use snippets instead.</p>
            <p>For example, you can use snippets for character-level styling (e.g., show a company name with italic, bold, and superscript text). The image below is not a variable, it is a snippet.</p>
            <p>
                <img src="../../../Images/Flare/Variables/Styled-Variables-Ex1-4.png" alt="" title="" class="MaxWidth100Percent" />
            </p>
            <p>Or, you can copy a symbol from a content file into the Variable Set Editor's plain text grid. The exact results of how a symbol might look in the output depends on the font type used.</p>
            <p>
                <img src="../../../Images/Flare/Variables/Styled-Variables-Ex2-7.png" alt="" title="" class="MaxWidth100Percent" />
            </p>
        </div>
    </body>
</html>